</picture></div></div><div
class="block-intro-text"><p>If you're a craft beer enthusiast, or if you want to cash in on the craft beer trend, you might be wondering how you can start a brewery. We've put together an easy step-by-step guide to help you navigate the entrepreneurial process, from choosing a brewery name to creating a production schedule, along with several helpful, downloadable resources.</p></div></div></div></div><div
class="section-content"><div
class="container"><div
class="narrow-container"><div
class="block"><p>While the beer market experienced a decline during the COVID-19 pandemic, the market has been on a steady growth path in the U.S. and is expected to be worth <a
href="https://www.statista.com/forecasts/944461/total-beer-market-size-in-the-us">$146 billion by 2025</a>.</p><p><strong>Craft breweries are booming.</strong> There are more than 9,000 craft breweries in the U.S. alone, according to the <a
href="https://www.brewersassociation.org/press-releases/brewers-association-midyear-survey-marks-maturing-craft-beer-market/">Brewers Association</a>. With tendentially more breweries opening than closing in the past years, this upward trend is also giving way to increased competitiveness in the craft brewery market.</p><p><strong>Domestically produced beer is favored by consumers.</strong> The beer market in the U.S. is dominated by locally produced beers, with imported beers accounting for only around <a
href="https://www.brewersassociation.org/statistics-and-data/national-beer-stats/">20% of the total market</a> in the U.S.</p></div><div
