</span>
1 Year</div></div><div
class="how-to-desc"><div
class="how-to-image">
<picture>
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-how-to-start-a-brewery-completed-800x800-20201006.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=250&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="250" height="250" alt="How to Start a Brewery:">
</picture></div><p>Breweries have a lot of moving parts — literally and figuratively. However, with the right preparation, your dream of owning a brewery can become a reality. Read through our 9-step guide to find out how.</p></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section1" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>1.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=choose-a-name-and-trademark-it>Choose a name and trademark it.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section1-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>1.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=think-about-what-makes-your-brewery-unique>Think about what makes your brewery unique.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-think-about-what-makes-your-brewery-unique-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Think about what makes your brewery unique."></div></div><p>Many breweries choose to adopt a name that relates to their location, such as Great Lakes Brewing. This can be a great way to create regional appeal, particularly in an industry that prides itself on "local" products. A unique name creates a stronger and more memorable first impression.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section1-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>1.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=perform-a-name-availability-search>Perform a name availability search.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-perform-a-name-availability-search-288x288-20200812.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Perform a name availability search."></div></div><p>Search to make sure no one else has taken your name. You can cross-check your idea by Googling the name and variations of it to find out if there is already a brewery in existence that bears the name you want to use. If there is, simply choose a different one.</p><p>If you can't find anything with a Google search, you can double-check by searching the United States Trademark and Patent database.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section1-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>1.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=trademark-your-name>Trademark your name.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-trademark-your-name-288x288-20200619.png?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Trademark your name."></div></div><p>File a trademark by filling out an application with the USPTO (United States Patent and Trademark Office). Attorneys at the USPTO will review your application to make sure that it complies with legal standards and does not conflict with existing trademarks.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section2" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>2.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=write-a-business-plan>Write a business plan.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section2-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>2.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=start-with-an-outline>Start with an outline.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-formulate-your-business-plan-288x288-20200820.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Start with an outline."></div></div><p>A business plan for a brewery should include the following items:</p><ul><li>Executive summary.</li><li>Business description.</li><li>Operations and management structure.</li><li>Marketing plan.</li><li>Competition analysis.</li><li>Financial data.</li><li>Future goals.</li></ul><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>This is a busy market, so the competition analysis portion of your business plan is very important. There are likely already several craft breweries in your region, so you will need to understand what they are doing and how your plan is distinct. To simplify things, start by asking yourself, "Why would customers buy my beer instead of the beer from brewery XYZ down the road?"</p></div><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>You can get a head start by using our free brewery business plan template toward the top of this page.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section2-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>2.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=create-a-detailed-financial-plan>Create a detailed financial plan.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-create-a-detailed-financial-plan-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Create a detailed financial plan."></div></div><p>As with most things in life, the financial portion of the plan is very important. If you are looking for people to invest in your brewery, you will need to provide as much financial information as possible.</p><p>This includes how much money you need to open, what your overhead costs will be, how many people you will employ, how much revenue you anticipate making, and so on.</p><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>Check out our pro forma profit and loss template below if you need a hand creating financial projections.</p></div></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section3" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>3.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=find-a-location>Find a location.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section3-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>3.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=choose-between-leasing-and-purchasing-a-property>Choose between leasing and purchasing a property.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-choose-between-leasing-and-purchasing-a-property-288x288-20200718.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Choose between leasing and purchasing a property."></div></div><p>Some new breweries are built from scratch so that they can be fully customized, while others are created by renovating an existing building. It's difficult to say which option is easier, but construction is sometimes better because breweries require a unique setup and retrofitting an old space can be complex and costly.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section3-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>3.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=determine-your-required-square-footage>Determine your required square footage.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-determine-your-required-square-footage-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Determine your required square footage."></div></div><p>According to <a
href="https://specificmechanical.com/">Specific Mechanical</a>, you can determine your square footage needs based on the volume of your production. They recommend the following guidelines:</p><ul><li>300 to 500 square feet for a 3-5 barrel system.</li><li>550 to 1200 square feet for a 7, 10, or 15 barrel system.</li></ul><p>Brewing facilities also need practical features like loading docks, ventilation from the brew kettle to the outside of the building, adequate ceiling height to accommodate brewing tanks, etc.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section4" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>4.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=form-a-legal-entity>Form a legal entity.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section4-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>4.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=choose-a-legal-structure>Choose a legal structure.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-familiarize-yourself-with-the-key-business-structures-288x288-20200820.png?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Choose a legal structure."></div></div><p>You can create a corporation, partnership, or LLC for your business. Setting a brewery up as a sole proprietorship wouldn't make sense, because you will likely need employees and have a tax burden that is too large for one person to carry on their own. Most local breweries start as a limited liability company (LLC).</p><p>In an LLC, ownership is usually limited to just a few people. This could also be said of a partnership, except partners must each bear some responsibility for taxes on their individual tax returns. In an LLC, you are only taxed on income that comes out of the company. Thus, when you're opening a brewery and reinvesting most of your initial profits, the tax consequences will be very minimal.</p><p>A further benefit of setting up your new brewery as an LLC is that it gives you greater control over how the company operates. In a business that is very hands-on, this control is important if you want to be able to grow and adapt.</p><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>Legal fees should be budgeted into your business plan, so find a law firm that you trust to manage your legal affairs. Some specialized law firms, such as <a
href="https://craftbeerattorney.com/">The Craft Beer Attorney</a>, actually specialize in working with clients in the craft beer industry. At the very least, you should have a lawyer with experience in corporate law so that your business is compliant with local, state, and federal laws.</p></div></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section5" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>5.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=hire-employees>Hire employees.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section5-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>5.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=list-what-positions-need-to-be-filled>List what positions need to be filled.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-list-what-positions-need-to-be-filled-288x288-20200811-1.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="List what positions need to be filled."></div></div><p>Operating a brewery is very labor intensive, so you will need at least a couple of employees, if not more.</p><p>Positions at a brewery typically include:</p><ul><li>Master Brewer.</li><li>Taproom Server.</li><li>Sales/Marketing Manager.</li><li>Packaging Worker.</li><li>Assistant Brewer.</li></ul><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p><strong>The Master Brewer is the person who is responsible for creating recipes,</strong> starting new batches of beer, monitoring progress, testing batches, and so on. Every brewery needs an experienced Master Brewer who understands the process from start to finish and knows how to control quality along the way so that you end up with a delicious finished product.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section5-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>5.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=advertise-job-opportunities>Advertise job opportunities.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-advertise-job-opportunities.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Advertise job opportunities."></div></div><p>List your job vacancies with complete descriptions on popular sites like Indeed and Monster. This will help you to get more exposure and attract the best workers in your region.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section5-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>5.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=train-new-employees>Train new employees.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-train-new-employees-288x288-20200723_2020-07-23-183109.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Train new employees."></div></div><p>You can train employees with no previous experience working in a brewery, but since there will be many other challenges when you are opening a brewery for the first time, it is advisable to hire people who already have some experience in the field. You can use hiring software and job posting software to help streamline your hiring process.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section6" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>6.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=get-a-license-from-the-ttb>Get a license from the TTB.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section6-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>6.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=visit-the-ttb-website>Visit the TTB website.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-visit-the-ttb-website-288x288-20200812.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Visit the TTB website."></div></div><p>The TTB is the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau, a department of the United States Treasury. Every brewery must obtain a Brewer's Notice from the TTB in order to operate legally in the United States. You can also access brewing industry resources on the <a
href="https://www.ttb.gov">TTB website</a>.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section6-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>6.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=navigate-to-the-quot-beer-resources-quot-section>Navigate to the &quot;beer resources&quot; section.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-navigate-to-the-beer-resources-section-288x288-20200812.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Navigate to the &quot;beer resources&quot; section."></div></div><p>On the beer resources page, you'll find a variety of helpful links for prospective brewers who want to know the ins and outs of brewing regulations.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section6-step3" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>6.3&nbsp;</span><h4 id=click-quot-brewer-039-s-notice-quot-then-quot-apply-online-quot>Click &quot;Brewer&#039;s Notice,&quot; then &quot;Apply Online.&quot;</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-click-brewers-notice-then-apply-online-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Click &quot;Brewer&#039;s Notice,&quot; then &quot;Apply Online.&quot;"></div></div><p>The link to the Brewer's Notice permit page will direct you to a set of instructions. From there, you can either start your online application (if you already have a TTB online account), or register for an account first.</p><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>When you are filling out the Brewer's Notice application form, it's best to include as much information as possible about your brewery. This will increase the chances of your application being accepted. Include details about your legal structure, your business location, and so on.</p></div><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>The TTB handles thousands of applications, so it may take over four months for yours to be processed. Keep in mind that you need to sign a lease before submitting the application, but your brewery cannot legally open until your application is approved. This delay can put a strain on your financial plan, so be flexible and try to make the most of the waiting period.</p></div></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section7" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>7.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=get-state-licenses>Get state licenses.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section7-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>7.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=find-out-what-licenses-are-applicable-in-your-state>Find out what licenses are applicable in your state.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-brewery-licenses-288x288-20230928.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Find out what licenses are applicable in your state."></div></div><p>To find out what licenses and permits you need, visit your state's small business website or contact the office of the small business development director. On the website, you should be able to find out what the essential requirements are for opening a brewery.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section8" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>8.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=choose-distributors>Choose distributors.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section8-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>8.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=build-relationships-in-the-industry>Build relationships in the industry.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-build-relationships-in-the-industry-288x288-20200812.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Build relationships in the industry."></div></div><p>If you want to get an early start on distribution by selling through retailers or restaurants, you will need to form partnerships and agreements that allow you to get your product from your brewery into customers' hands via a middle man.</p><p>Talk to local restaurant owners and ask them if they would be willing to use one of their bar taps for your beer. Restaurant patrons usually want local beer options, and it can be a great way to earn customers by giving them easy access to your beer in a place where they already like to go.</p></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section8-step2" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>8.2&nbsp;</span><h4 id=talk-to-retailers>Talk to retailers.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-talk-to-retailers-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Talk to retailers."></div></div><p>You can meet with retail store owners and ask them if they would be interested in carrying your product. Starting on a trial basis will allow store owners to see how well the product sells, and strong sales could lead to increased orders.</p></div></div></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section9" class="how-to-section"><div
class="section-title">
<span>9.&nbsp;</span><h3 id=create-a-brewing-production-schedule>Create a brewing production schedule.</h3></div><div
id="how-to-start-a-brewery-section9-step1" class="step"><div
class="step-desc"><div
class="step-title">
<span>9.1&nbsp;</span><h4 id=analyze-sales-data>Analyze sales data.</h4></div><div
class="image-wrapper"><div
class="image-holder">
<img
data-src="https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-analyze-sales-data-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2" class="lazyload" width="144" height="144" alt="Analyze sales data."></div></div><p>With a schedule, you can keep up with the demand for each of the various beer flavors that you offer. As your sales increase, you will start to notice trends and you can adjust the schedule according to demand. For example, if one beer is more popular among patrons than the others, you could add an extra brewing cycle.</p><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>A brewing schedule can be created using a spreadsheet, or other scheduling software. Use whatever is most convenient for you and make sure it can be accessed and modified by your Master Brewer. Check out our free brewing production schedule template at the bottom of the page.</p></div><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>You should be careful not to over-extend yourself. When you start a new brewery, it can be tempting to ramp up production in order to pay for all of the equipment that you've just purchased. On the other hand, it can be equally tempting to experiment with recipes and start with a small production volume. You need to strike a balance that addresses your cash flow needs and maintains the quality of the beer.</p></div><div
class="step-tip">
<span
class="icon">
<svg
xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" x="0px" y="0px" viewBox="0 0 512 512" style="enable-background:new 0 0 512 512;" xml:space="preserve">
<g>
<path
d="M256,0C114.844,0,0,114.844,0,256s114.844,256,256,256s256-114.844,256-256S397.156,0,256,0z M298.667,416    c0,5.896-4.771,10.667-10.667,10.667h-64c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667V256h-10.667c-5.896,0-10.667-4.771-10.667-10.667    v-42.667c0-5.896,4.771-10.667,10.667-10.667H288c5.896,0,10.667,4.771,10.667,10.667V416z M256,170.667    c-23.531,0-42.667-19.135-42.667-42.667S232.469,85.333,256,85.333s42.667,19.135,42.667,42.667S279.531,170.667,256,170.667z" data-original="#000000" class="active-path" data-old_color="#000000" fill="#4949E7"/>
</g>
</svg>
</span><p>Veteran brewers recommend working in another brewery to familiarize yourself with the brewing cycle before going out on your own. This knowledge will help you - as an owner -  to understand the dynamics of the brewing process.</p></div></div></div></div></div> <script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"http://schema.org","@type":"HowTo","name":"How to Start a Brewery","description":"<p>Breweries have a lot of moving parts \u2014 literally and figuratively. However, with the right preparation, your dream of owning a brewery can become a reality. Read through our 9-step guide to find out how.<\/p>\n","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-how-to-start-a-brewery-completed-800x800-20201006.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=250&dpr=2","height":"800","width":"800"},"estimatedCost":{"@type":"MonetaryAmount","currency":"USD","value":"550,000.00"},"totalTime":"P1Y","step":[{"@type":"HowToSection","position":"1","name":"<p>Choose a name and trademark it.<\/p>\n","itemListElement":[{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"1","name":"<p>Think about what makes your brewery unique.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Many breweries choose to adopt a name that relates to their location, such as Great Lakes Brewing. This can be a great way to create regional appeal, particularly in an industry that prides itself on \"local\" products. A unique name creates a stronger and more memorable first impression.<\/p>\n","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/guides/how-to-start-a-brewery#how-to-start-a-brewery-section1-step1","image":{"@type":"ImageObject","url":"https://www.notzarla.com/images/zarla-think-about-what-makes-your-brewery-unique-288x288-20200811.jpeg?crop=1:1,smart&width=144&dpr=2","height":"288","width":"288"}},{"@type":"HowToStep","position":"2","name":"<p>Perform a name availability search.<\/p>\n","text":"<p>Search to make sure no one else has taken your name. You can cross-check your idea by Googling the name and variations of it to find out if there is alread